# PowerShell Coding Standards

## Naming Conventions
- **Cmdlet/Function Names**: Must use the standard `Verb-Noun` format (e.g., `Get-NtnxVm`, `New-NtnxCluster`).
  - Use `Get-Verb` to verify approved verbs.
  - Prefix Nouns with `Ntnx` or a project-specific prefix to avoid collisions.
- **Variables**: Use `CamelCase` for parameters and local variables (e.g., `$vmName`, `$clusterConfig`).
- **Constants**: Use `UPPER_CASE` for script-wide constants (e.g., `$MAX_RETRIES`).

## Style & Structure
- **Parameter Splatting**: ALWAYS use splatting for cmdlets with more than 3 parameters to improve readability.
- **Output**: Return objects (`PSCustomObject`), not text. Do not use `Write-Host` for data return; use `Write-Output` or direct object emission.
- **Comments**: Use "Better Comments" style:
  - `# ! Critical alert`
  - `# ? Question/Explanation`
  - `# TODO: Future work`

## Error Handling
- **Strict Mode**: Scripts must start with `Set-StrictMode -Version Latest`.
- **ErrorAction**: Default to `$ErrorActionPreference = 'Stop'` for production scripts.
- **Try/Catch**: Wrap all external calls (API, File I/O) in `try { } catch { }` blocks.
  - In `catch` blocks, capture specific exception types when possible (e.g., `[System.Net.WebException]`).

## Examples

@example
# Good: Parameter Splatting and Verb-Noun
function Get-NtnxVmConfig {
    [CmdletBinding()]
    param (
        [string]$VmName,
        [string]$ClusterId
    )

    $params = @{
        Uri     = "https://api.nutanix.com/..."
        Method  = "GET"
        Headers = $AuthHeaders
    }
    Invoke-RestMethod @params
}

# Bad: Long lines and Write-Host
function getVM {
    $data = Invoke-RestMethod -Uri "..." -Method GET -Headers ...
    Write-Host $data.name
}